# TypeScript Rules

## Any Type

- **NEVER use the `any` type** - This defeats the purpose of TypeScript's type safety
- Instead of `any`, use proper typing, generics, or `unknown` for truly unknown data
- If you must use `any`, add a TODO comment explaining why and plan to fix it

```typescript
// Bad
const data: any = fetchData();
const items: any[] = getItems();

// Good
const data: UserData = fetchData();
const items: Item[] = getItems();

// Good — unknown when shape is not known at compile time
const unknownData: unknown = fetchUnknownData();
if (typeof unknownData === 'object' && unknownData !== null) {
    const data = unknownData as Record<string, unknown>;
}
```

## Type Casting

- **AVOID type casting at all costs** - Casting (for example, `as SomeType`) can hide real typing problems and bypass TypeScript safety checks
- Prefer safer alternatives first: proper type definitions, narrowing with type guards, generics, and runtime validation
- If there is absolutely no way around a type cast, include an inline comment explaining why the cast is necessary

```typescript
// Bad
const user = response as User;

// Good
if (typeof response === 'object' && response !== null && 'id' in response) {
    const user = response;
}

// Good — last resort only; comment why the cast is required
// Third-party API returns untyped payload and cannot be changed
const payload = externalResult as ExternalPayload;
```

## Non-null Assertion Operator

- **NEVER use the non-null assertion operator (`!`)** - This operator tells TypeScript to ignore potential null/undefined values, which can lead to runtime errors
- Instead of using `!`, use proper null checks, optional chaining (`?.`), or type guards
- If you're certain a value exists, prove it with validation/type guards before usage

```typescript
// Bad
const user = getUser()!;
const name = user.name!;

// Good
const user = getUser();
if (user?.name) {
    const name = user.name;
}
```
